WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.640
I'm Michael Thomas. I'm the Chief Data Scientist at Ketchbrook Analytics, which is a data science

00:00:09.640 --> 00:00:16.920
consulting firm, and believe it or not, we use both R and Python together. This is a

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:22.320
LinkedIn post that was making the rounds a few months ago. Maybe it sounds like some

00:00:22.320 --> 00:00:28.520
of you in this room may have seen it. It got a lot of buzz online, reigniting the so-called

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:35.520
language wars that were reminiscent of the pre-Elon Twitter days, but I digress. My experience

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:41.720
with the R versus Python debate is a little bit different, and it doesn't take a side.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:46.680
So this might be a hot take, but I believe that almost everything that used to make Python

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:52.540
awesome that wasn't in R has since been ported over to R, and vice versa. Everything that

00:00:52.540 --> 00:00:57.680
used to make R awesome that wasn't in Python has since been ported over to Python.

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:03.480
So Michael, if all of the good stuff is in both languages, then why not just pick one?

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:09.040
I can think of at least three reasons why. First, if you're looking for good data science

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:13.800
candidates to build out your team, limiting your search to only individuals that know

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:20.800
one language or the other can slow the hiring process. Second, once in a while, I will run

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:25.559
into a problem where there's a package in one language that solves that problem that

00:01:25.559 --> 00:01:32.199
doesn't exist in the other language. Lastly, I work at a consulting firm, and the fact

00:01:32.199 --> 00:01:37.419
that we can offer our clients the option to choose which language we're going to build

00:01:37.419 --> 00:01:43.120
their solution in is a huge value proposition for us.

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:47.360
So now that I've clearly convinced you that a multilingual data science team can have

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:53.599
a lot of benefits, I'm going to let you in on the secret to actually making that work.

00:01:53.639 --> 00:01:57.879
And this is going to sound non-technical, but I've found that the key to making multilingual

00:01:57.879 --> 00:02:03.160
data science teams work is an extra dose of empathy. And I'd argue that empathy is an

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:08.399
important ingredient in any data science team, but especially so for teams that are trying

00:02:08.399 --> 00:02:11.199
to use R and Python together.

00:02:11.199 --> 00:02:16.960
And I want to focus on the technical things that you can do that are empathetic towards

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:22.880
others on your team. And I'm going to break it down into three areas. Environment management,

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:28.279
package choices, and documentation. And I like to think of these as the three pillars

00:02:28.279 --> 00:02:33.960
of technical empathy, and we'll revisit this pillar concept throughout this presentation.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:40.520
And let's start with the first pillar, environment management. In the pillar of environment management,

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:45.320
empathy means helping your team spend more time creating value and less time troubleshooting

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:49.000
technical issues.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.860
But it works on my machine. Have any of you ever heard this phrase, maybe even uttered

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:58.199
it yourself? A little show of hands out there. I won't ask you if you've said it yourself,

00:02:58.199 --> 00:03:03.199
but at least heard it. There are still lots of folks dealing with this today, day in and

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:08.800
day out. And there are also people that don't care because they're essentially a lone wolf.

00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:13.199
And I still think that those people should care about this. It's a short-sighted approach.

00:03:13.199 --> 00:03:17.679
But today we're focusing on data science teams, not lone wolves. And the idea that

00:03:17.679 --> 00:03:22.639
you want the code that you're writing on your own laptop to also run successfully somewhere

00:03:22.639 --> 00:03:25.199
else.

00:03:25.199 --> 00:03:31.440
I believe successful environment management boils down to consistency across three things.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:37.199
The operating system, the version of Python or R that you're using, and the versions of

00:03:37.199 --> 00:03:42.000
the individual R or Python packages that you're using on that project.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.679
So let's talk about the first two. On the operating system and Python or R version side,

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:52.399
you can typically use the same tooling for managing both of those. There are two best

00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:58.720
approaches to doing this, leveraging third-party tools like Posit Workbench, hosted on a dedicated

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:04.080
server or cloud environment, that allow you to set up your environment in a more simplified

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:07.160
kind of point-and-click approach.

00:04:07.160 --> 00:04:11.119
Or you can leverage open source tooling where you will essentially script your environment.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:15.839
And if you choose to go that open source approach, know that it's going to require some DevOps

00:04:15.839 --> 00:04:19.760
skill sets. So you'll need to ask yourself if that's something you want to undertake

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:25.359
or not, and weigh that against the cost benefit of something like a Posit Workbench that abstracts

00:04:25.359 --> 00:04:27.720
a lot of that away from you.

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:32.920
On the package versioning side, using virtual environments, which allow you to manage package

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:39.720
versions on a project-by-project basis, instead of having some sort of global package library,

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:44.519
can be really efficient for collaboration and ensuring that you and the rest of your

00:04:44.519 --> 00:04:48.959
team are working within the same setup. And I think that there are essentially two leaders

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:55.959
these days in that area, UV on the Python side and Renv on the R side.

00:04:57.239 --> 00:05:01.920
So we just talked about package versions, but now let's talk about choosing which packages

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:08.920
to use at all. In the second pillar of package choices, empathy means syntax similarity for

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:13.760
easier code review and collaboration.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:18.559
Here's a big question that I ask myself every day. How easy would it be for someone who

00:05:18.559 --> 00:05:25.279
knows R to review my Python code, or vice versa? And the choice of packages you use

00:05:25.279 --> 00:05:31.440
can really impact how successful your multilingual data science team will be.

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:36.480
In these next few slides, you'll see R code examples on the left-hand side of the screen

00:05:36.519 --> 00:05:40.359
and Python code examples on the right side of the screen.

00:05:40.359 --> 00:05:44.320
And this somewhat goes back to my slide where I mentioned that everything great in each

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:48.880
language had been ported to the other language. But I really think it actually goes beyond

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:53.959
that. I think the great ideas are being borrowed from each language.

00:05:53.959 --> 00:06:00.239
And the Python package Polars is a great example. The author of Polars, Richie Vink, he's mentioned

00:06:00.239 --> 00:06:04.640
in a bunch of interviews that Polars takes a lot of inspiration from the tidyverse in

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:09.399
R. And in a minute here, I think we'll show you just how true that is.

00:06:09.399 --> 00:06:15.160
And we know that data prep is 80% of data science. So the methodology and the opinions

00:06:15.160 --> 00:06:19.119
that you choose are a significant investment for your team.

00:06:19.119 --> 00:06:25.440
At Ketchbook, our choice is typically Polars for Python data prep and Dplyr for R data

00:06:25.440 --> 00:06:30.559
prep because not only are they two of the most popular data wrangling libraries in their

00:06:30.559 --> 00:06:35.519
respective languages, but they're also syntactically really, really similar.

00:06:35.519 --> 00:06:41.359
If you want to filter data in your data frame, use the filter function in either package

00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:47.859
and specify the column and its constraint. Do you need to select a column or a specific

00:06:47.859 --> 00:06:53.160
set of columns? Use the select verb. And because nothing is completely perfect, we

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:59.000
have the arrange verb in Dplyr and sort in Polars with some slight differences in direction

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:03.959
such that descending is actually a function in Dplyr, whereas it's an argument on the

00:07:03.959 --> 00:07:05.959
Polars side.

00:07:05.959 --> 00:07:11.540
But lastly, we have the trusty head function from Base R and in Polars for grabbing the

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:16.679
first five rows of data after the upstream ETL takes place. And these are just a few

00:07:16.679 --> 00:07:21.720
functions, but if you went out today and you further explored the Dplyr and the Polars

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:27.440
packages, you'll continue to find these syntax similarities all over the place.

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:32.679
Now, Polars is already pretty good at this, but in situations where you may need to manipulate

00:07:32.679 --> 00:07:38.279
quote, unquote, big data, whatever that means these days, you could opt for the arrow R

00:07:38.279 --> 00:07:43.640
package to continue to leverage a lot of that Dplyr syntax that you may be used to.

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:47.959
But on multilingual teams, there's another interesting option that's perhaps even more

00:07:47.959 --> 00:07:52.920
language agnostic. It's actually courtesy of a PositConf keynote speaker last year,

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:59.079
and that's DuckDB. If you haven't heard of it, DuckDB is a zero-dependency analytics

00:07:59.079 --> 00:08:04.839
database engine that allows you to do data wrangling in SQL at lightning-fast speeds.

00:08:04.839 --> 00:08:10.000
I'm underselling it. If you haven't tried it, I really encourage you to check it out.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:16.839
But beyond that, we have great libraries in both R and Python that allow us to call DuckDB.

00:08:16.839 --> 00:08:21.839
In each language, there's a bit of setup in the front to connect to the database and some

00:08:21.839 --> 00:08:27.640
small syntactic differences at the end of the script. But everything in the middle is

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:36.760
exactly the same. The year is 2025 and SQL will not die. In fact, I'd argue that perhaps

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:43.359
it's as popular and hot as ever. And using DuckDB is a great way to still have a high-powered

00:08:43.359 --> 00:08:47.299
analytics engine that's easily portable across languages.

00:08:47.299 --> 00:08:53.140
If I had a longer version of this data wrangling script in R and suddenly I needed to port

00:08:53.140 --> 00:08:57.340
my project over to Python instead, the only things I would need to change would be that

00:08:57.340 --> 00:09:02.820
little tiny bit of code at the beginning of my script and at the end of my script.

00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:09.380
Let's take a look at another example, ggplot2 in R and plot9 in Python. With the exception

00:09:09.380 --> 00:09:15.179
of quoting column names and wrapping the entire expression in parentheses on the Python side,

00:09:15.179 --> 00:09:22.460
the code is literally identical. And one last example I'll give is gt in R versus greattables

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:29.460
in Python. Cue the office meme with Pam saying they're literally the same picture.

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:34.539
And these last two examples I just gave are no accident. Posit is behind all four of these

00:09:34.539 --> 00:09:42.460
packages, ggplot2, plot9, gt, and greattables. And they have put a lot of work into structuring

00:09:42.460 --> 00:09:49.979
these packages in a way that preserves a ton of syntax similarity.

00:09:49.979 --> 00:09:56.299
And our final pillar today, documentation. Empathy means providing clear guides and road

00:09:56.299 --> 00:10:04.159
maps for collaborators, including your future self. So here's my public service announcement.

00:10:04.159 --> 00:10:10.179
Please treat documentation as a first-class citizen in your software development practices.

00:10:10.179 --> 00:10:16.380
Years ago, I heard someone say, I think it was J.D. Long, that software shouldn't be

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:21.859
a bunch of code with a little bit of documentation. Actually, the ratio should be the inverse.

00:10:21.859 --> 00:10:25.619
It should be a lot of documentation with a little bit of code.

00:10:25.619 --> 00:10:31.940
Now, I'm going to talk about documentation in the context of, A, function documentation,

00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:41.219
and, B, what I'm going to call Git-based documentation, such as issues and pull requests.

00:10:41.219 --> 00:10:45.340
Consider this simple function I've put together that rounds a number to a certain number of

00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:50.099
digits and forces it to round up. You don't need to care about what it's doing, and the

00:10:50.099 --> 00:10:55.780
syntax is very similar across both R and Python. But the point here is going to be around the

00:10:55.780 --> 00:11:03.460
documentation of the function. In R, we have ROxygen as the prevailing framework

00:11:03.460 --> 00:11:08.219
for function documentation. In Python, we have a couple of options and a little bit

00:11:08.219 --> 00:11:14.299
more flexibility. The prevailing two options seem to be either Google or SciPy's approach

00:11:14.299 --> 00:11:19.700
to doc strings. Within our team at Ketchbook, we tend to go with the SciPy approach, really

00:11:19.700 --> 00:11:25.539
only because I find it a little bit more readable, and I know SciPy, as an organization, is data

00:11:25.539 --> 00:11:32.539
science-focused. So let's compare the ROxygen framework to the Python SciPy framework.

00:11:32.539 --> 00:11:37.500
In both cases, you can kind of just stick your function description at the beginning

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:44.900
of your documentation. Function arguments are defined in param tags in R and under a

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:50.820
parameter section in Python. And you might note that Python tends to traditionally be

00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:57.179
more explicit about supplying argument data types than we're used to in R. While it's

00:11:57.179 --> 00:12:04.580
not required by ROxygen, we've tried to adopt that in R as well. And the output of the function

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:11.719
is documented in a returns tag or section in both languages. And examples are always

00:12:11.719 --> 00:12:17.440
critical and similarly structured in both cases. So when we leverage these parallels

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:22.280
in how we document our functions across the two languages, it's yet another relatively

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:31.000
simple way that we can make it easier to cross the language aisle and work together.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:37.119
So jumping now to our approach to what I'll call GitHub documentation via issues and pull

00:12:37.119 --> 00:12:42.520
requests. If you're on a data science team, there are probably a few approaches to how

00:12:42.520 --> 00:12:47.400
you could structure your collaborative workflows. I'm going to show you our current approach,

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:53.000
which I believe is not only ours, but very similar to organizations that we've seen,

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:58.239
including Posit. So the first step would be a user or a developer identifies a bug in

00:12:58.239 --> 00:13:03.119
the software or comes up with an enhancement that they're suggesting we implement. And

00:13:03.119 --> 00:13:08.760
they write this up in a detailed issue. Once that issue has been created, when we're ready

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:14.840
to actually work on making the required code changes, we first create a new Git branch

00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:20.880
in the repository, specifically for the purposes of addressing that issue. Then the developer

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:26.479
goes off and writes or modifies the code that fixes the bug or adds the enhancement. And

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:30.440
once the developer feels like the updated code is in a good spot, they can write up

00:13:30.440 --> 00:13:36.599
a pull request or a PR for short that details how they addressed the issue, what changed,

00:13:36.599 --> 00:13:42.960
and more. So let's focus first on issues. In my opinion,

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:48.320
I think a good issue is comprised of three different parts. First, an overview of the

00:13:48.320 --> 00:13:52.760
bug that you're encountering or the enhancement that you're proposing, including the rationale

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:58.640
for why you feel a change to the code base is necessary. Second, a reprex, a reproducible

00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:05.320
example, a.k.a. some code that someone else can run to show that current shortfall that

00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:10.919
the proposed enhancement will overcome or identify the bug. And lastly, a discussion

00:14:10.919 --> 00:14:17.280
which may or may not include code regarding possible solutions. So I thought I'd show

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:23.119
an example of a real-world GitHub issue we've authored that contains this structure. An

00:14:23.119 --> 00:14:30.400
overview section, a reproducible example section with some code that can be run, and a possible

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:39.960
solution that's being included as well. On the pull request side, it's very similar.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:45.919
A good pull request, in my opinion, is also comprised of three parts. First, the purpose

00:14:45.919 --> 00:14:52.599
of the pull request and the associated issue or issues that it addresses. Second, a more

00:14:52.599 --> 00:14:58.880
in-the-weeds section that details the technical aspects of how the issue was addressed in

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:04.840
code as well as any design decisions that were made and any hurdles that were overcome

00:15:04.840 --> 00:15:10.919
along the way. Lastly, instructions and code that a reviewer can run in order to see the

00:15:10.919 --> 00:15:16.640
impact of the changes that you made. So I'm going to pick on Ivan on our team in the front

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:21.479
row for a minute here because he does an awesome job at this. And here's an example of a GitHub

00:15:21.479 --> 00:15:27.080
pull request he authored containing those three components I just mentioned. An overview

00:15:27.080 --> 00:15:33.440
section, a detail section, a test section, and even a discussion section that, in this

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:37.479
case, provided some additional context that he felt was important for the reviewer to

00:15:37.479 --> 00:15:43.599
know. In the interest of time, I won't show more examples beyond issues and pull requests

00:15:43.599 --> 00:15:49.520
today, but we also take a standardized approach to our READMEs in each repository as well,

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:54.960
making sure to document at a bare minimum the purpose of the repository and the project's

00:15:54.960 --> 00:16:00.080
background, the prerequisites or dependencies that you'll need to run the code, and how

00:16:00.080 --> 00:16:06.599
to use the software. So let's put this all back together here. I think it's easy to say

00:16:06.599 --> 00:16:12.719
that successful team collaboration requires empathy, but these are the technical ways

00:16:12.719 --> 00:16:17.599
that we've hacked empathy within our multilingual data science team that seems to be keeping

00:16:17.599 --> 00:16:22.239
everyone happy and productive. Lastly, I want to make a couple quick shout-outs. Thank you

00:16:22.239 --> 00:16:28.080
to Posit and Articulation, as well as Emily Reederer. I wanted to mention her. She previously

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:33.119
gave a talk called Python Argonomics, which was a big inspiration for this talk, and how

00:16:33.119 --> 00:16:37.640
we think about multilingual data science at Ketchbook. If you haven't seen it, I recommend

00:16:37.640 --> 00:16:41.840
you checking it out. I think it's a nice compliment if you're interested in exploring this topic

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:47.919
further. And if you'd like to get in touch with me, you can find me on LinkedIn, BlueSky,

00:16:47.919 --> 00:16:49.919
GitHub, or through our company website.

00:16:49.919 --> 00:17:03.840
All right. We have time for a question or two. Do you see R-like Python packages like

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:10.199
Plot9 or Polars being used more outside of just multilingual teams? How transferable

00:17:10.199 --> 00:17:15.839
are these skills to purely Python teams versus using more standardized packages like Pandas

00:17:15.839 --> 00:17:16.839
or Matplotlib?

00:17:16.839 --> 00:17:22.839
That's a good question. I think I'm sure that there's a lot of legacy code and workflows

00:17:22.839 --> 00:17:28.079
that folks have on teams that are typically just using one language or the other. But

00:17:28.079 --> 00:17:32.920
I think you have to think about the rationale for why these packages were created in the

00:17:32.920 --> 00:17:37.800
first place. And I think Hadley said something interesting either yesterday or the day before,

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:43.839
where the idea is to be able to get what's in your brain out as fast as possible, right,

00:17:43.839 --> 00:17:47.680
with maybe as little code in the middle. And I think a lot of these packages that we're

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:52.000
talking about, Plot9, Polars, some of the newer advancements, are trying to do that

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.800
regardless of whether you care about them being multilingual or not.

00:17:55.800 --> 00:18:01.079
Okay. One more. Do you think there's a need for Python versions of the dev tools or use

00:18:01.079 --> 00:18:02.079
as packages?

00:18:02.079 --> 00:18:03.079
Yes.

00:18:03.079 --> 00:18:07.680
Sure. I mean, it's fine with me.

00:18:07.680 --> 00:18:13.199
Yes. I think there's much more, I guess, standardization and obviously enforcement

00:18:13.199 --> 00:18:17.000
on the R side in terms of package development that's lacking on the Python side that could

